82":"1382","1370":"1370","1408":"1408","Tilney, Norfolk, England":"Tilney St Lawrence, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Congham, Kings Lynn and West Norfolk Borough, Norfolk, England":"Congham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Congham, Norfolk, England":"Congham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","King's Lynn, Norfolk, England":"King's Lynn, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Norreys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Norris  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Norris","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Middle English <i>norreis</i>, <i>noreis</i>, <i>norais</i> ‘northerner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>noreis</i>), used both of Norwegians and of inhabitants of northern England and Scotland.","from the Middle English personal name <i>Norreis</i>, derived from <i>norreis</i> ‘northerner’."]}]},{"name":"Geoffrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic (Frankish and Lombard) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It was in regular use among the counts of Anjou, ancestors of the English royal house of Plantagenet, who were descended from Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou (  1113–51 ). It was a particularly popular name in England and France in the later Middle Ages; notable bearers in England include the poet  Geoffrey Chaucer  (  <i>c.</i>1340–1400 ) and in Wales the chronicler  Geoffrey  of Monmouth (  d. 1155 ). The original form and meaning of the name is disputed. According to one theory, it is merely a variant of   Godfrey ;  others derive the first part from the Germanic word <i>gawia</i> ‘territory’, <i>walah</i> ‘stranger’, or <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. Medieval forms can be found to support all these theories, and it is possible that several names have fallen together, or that the name was subjected to reanalysis by folk etymology at an early date."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Geoffrey Norreys was born in 1370, in Tilney St Lawrence, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Geoffrey Norreys, was 30 and his mother, Alice, was 28. He had at least 2 sons. He died in 1408, in Congham, Norfolk, England, at the age of 38, and was buried in Congham, Norfolk, England."},"et":{"1370–1408":"1370–1408","1404–Male":"1404–Surnud","1408–1464":"1408–1464","1340–1382":"1340–1382","1342–1370":"1342–1370","1404":"1404","1365":"1365","1464":"1464","1342":"1342","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1408":"1408","Tilney, Norfolk, England":"Tilney St Lawrence, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Congham, Kings Lynn and West Norfolk Borough, Norfolk, England":"Congham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Congham, Norfolk, England":"Congham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","King's Lynn, Norfolk, England":"King's Lynn, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1370–1408":"1370–1408","1404–Male":"1404–Kuollut","1408–1464":"1408–1464","1340–1382":"1340–1382","1342–1370":"1342–1370","1404":"1404","1365":"1365","1464":"1464","1342":"1342","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1408":"1408","Tilney, Norfolk, England":"Tilney St Lawrence, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Congham, Kings Lynn and West Norfolk Borough, Norfolk, England":"Congham, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Congham, Norfolk, England":"Congham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","King's Lynn, Nor